HOUSE BILL 286
R5 6lr0148
(PRE–FILED) CF SB 38
By: Chair, Judiciary Committee (By Request – Departmental – Transportation)
Requested: September 26, 2025
Introduced and read first time: January 14, 2026
Assigned to: Judiciary
A BILL ENTITLED
1 AN ACT concerning
2 Vehicle Laws – Ignition Interlock System Program – Required Participation
3 FOR the purpose of requiring an individual to be a participant in the Ignition Interlock
4 System Program as a condition of modification of a suspension or revocation of a
5 license or issuance of a restricted license if the individual violated certain alcohol
6 restrictions; and generally relating to required participation in the Ignition Interlock
7 System Program.
8 BY repealing and reenacting, without amendments,
9 Article – Transportation
10 Section 16–404.1(a) through (c)
11 Annotated Code of Maryland
12 (2020 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
13 BY repealing and reenacting, with amendments,
14 Article – Transportation
15 Section 16–404.1(d)(2)
16 Annotated Code of Maryland
17 (2020 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
18 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
19 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
20 Article – Transportation
21 16–404.1.
22 (a) (1) In this section the following words have the meanings indicated.
23 (2) “Approved service provider” means a person who is certified by:
EXPLANATION: CAPITALS INDICATE MATTER ADDED TO EXISTING LAW.
[Brackets] indicate matter deleted from exist in g l aw . *hb0286*

2 HOUSE BILL 286
1 (i) The Administration to service, install, monitor, calibrate, and
2 provide information on ignition interlock systems; and
3 (ii) A manufacturer to be qualified to service, install, monitor,
4 calibrate, and provide information on ignition interlock systems.
5 (3) “Manufacturer” means a person who manufactures ignition interlock
6 systems and who certifies that approved service providers are qualified to service, install,
7 monitor, calibrate, and provide information on ignition interlock systems.
8 (4) “Participant” means a participant in the Ignition Interlock System
9 Program.
10 (5) “Program” means the Ignition Interlock System Program.
11 (b) (1) The Administration shall establish an Ignition Interlock System
12 Program in accordance with this section.
13 (2) The Administration shall establish a protocol for the Program by
14 regulations that require certain minimum standards for all service providers who service,
15 install, monitor, calibrate, and provide information on ignition interlock systems and
16 include requirements that:
17 (i) A service provider who applies to the Administration for
18 certification as an approved service provider shall demonstrate that the service provider is
19 able to competently service, install, monitor, calibrate, and provide information to the
20 Administration at least every 30 days on individuals required to use ignition interlock
21 systems;
22 (ii) A service provider who applies to the Administration for
23 certification as an approved service provider shall be certified by a signed affidavit from
24 the manufacturer that the service provider has been trained by an authorized
25 manufacturer and that the service provider is competent to service, install, monitor,
26 calibrate, and provide information on ignition interlock systems;
27 (iii) Approved service providers be deemed to be authorized
28 representatives of a manufacturer; and
29 (iv) Any service of notice upon an approved service provider, who has
30 violated any laws or regulations or whose ignition interlock system has violated any laws
31 or regulations, be deemed as service upon the manufacturer who certified the approved
32 service provider.
33 (c) An individual may be a participant if:

HOUSE BILL 286 3
1 (1) The individual’s license is suspended or revoked under § 16–205 of this
2 title for a violation of § 21–902(c) of this article or § 16–404 of this subtitle for an
3 accumulation of points under § 16–402(a)(29) of this subtitle for driving while impaired by
4 a drug, a combination of drugs, or a combination of one or more drugs and alcohol;
5 (2) The individual’s license has an alcohol restriction imposed under §
6 16–113(g)(1) of this title; or
7 (3) The Administration modifies a suspension or issues a restricted license
8 to the individual under § 16–205.1 of this title.
9 (d) (2) (i) Notwithstanding subsection (c) of this section, an individual
10 shall be a participant as a condition of modification of a suspension or revocation of a license
11 or issuance of a restricted license if the individual:
12 1. Is required to be a participant by a court order under §
13 21–902.2 of this article; [or]
14 2. Was under the age of 21 years on the date of a violation by
15 the individual of[:] § 21–902(C) OF THIS ARTICLE; OR
16 [A.] 3. [An] VIOLATED AN alcohol restriction imposed
17 under [§ 16–113(b)(1) of] this title[; or
18 B. § 21–902(c) of this article].
19 (ii) If an individual is subject to this paragraph and the individual
20 fails to participate in the Program or does not successfully complete the Program, the
21 Administration shall suspend the individual’s license for 1 year.
22 (iii) Nothing contained in this paragraph limits the authority of the
23 Administration to modify a suspension imposed under this paragraph to allow an
24 individual to be a participant in accordance with subsection (e) or (o) of this section.
25 (iv) The Administration shall issue a restricted license to an
26 individual who is required to participate in the Program under this section and who is
27 otherwise eligible.
28 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect
29 October 1, 2026.

